Save this post for an easy, kid-friendly Christmas craft! 🎅🏼🎄 Bonus, they always turn out adorable and they make your house smell amazing! Here’s how to make your own cinnamon applesauce ornaments...

YOU NEED:
1 cup applesauce (smooth, unsweetened) 
1.25 - 1.5 cups cinnamon 

DIRECTIONS:
1. mix apple sauce and cinnamon in a bowl
2. add more cinnamon until you can squeeze dough into a ball and it holds together
3. chill slightly in fridge (20 mins at least)
4. once chilled, sprinkle work surface with cinnamon and roll balls until 1/3” thick. continue adding cinnamon if dough feels too tacky and is sticking to roller or surface
5. cut out shapes with cookie cutters
6. put a small hole in the top of each for string OR twist some floral wire to make a loop
7. bake in over at 200F for about 3 hours or until totally dried out and hardened 
8. add your strings, paint if you would like

A couple of little tips. One, dough consistency is key. Make sure your dough is wet enough to stick together but not so wet it’s sticking to your surface or cookie cutters. This will make cutting your shapes out easier! Two, after you’ve cut your shapes, gently flatten the edges to prevent your ornaments from looking “shaggy.” Three, flip after 1.5 hours of making to make sure the underside dries out properly! Drying them fully will allow them to keep year after year. 

Let me know if you’ve ever made these before!! If you try them out this year, tag me so I can see your creations!! ⛄️❄️

24 weeks (well actually 25 now but who’s counting) for this little baby and I. 🕊️ Thankful that 2022 brought us you and excited that you’ll be in our arms in 2023. What’s something you’re looking forward to in 2023? ✨

Dear 2022, you were a joy. Bring on 2023✨ 

When I look back at this past year, it’s not the big moments that stand out to me. 2022 brought us some pretty big and wonderful moments, but when I think about this past year the thing that makes my heart sing is all the little moments. It’s the culmination of these small moments, our day to day, that made this year special. It’s the Saturday morning art time, park dates, and watching my boys’ friendship blossom. It’s the walks around the neighborhood, weekly play dates with friends, and building family traditions. It’s the meals shared, the books read, and the relationships deepened that made 2022 wonderful. 

And despite how many highs 2022 gave us, it wasn’t with it without its lows too. Like every year, 2022 was full of ups and down. For all the happiness and joy it brought, there were also moments of loss, grief, questioning. It had its fair share of learning curves and growing pains. There was loss and letting go. Life is unpredictable. It can be beautiful and devastating in the same breath. I’ve learned that it’s almost impossible to control the things that are thrown our way. But this year taught me that I CAN control the way I respond and my perspective through the challenges. So while 2022 wasn’t perfect, I choose to look back on it with joy. 

I’m looking forward to 2023 and all the possibilities the new year brings with it. I’m not one for setting big goals at the beginning of the year but my hope for 2023 is to simply be more intentional. More intentional with my time, with what I consume, and with the people I choose to pour into. I hope to be more present, to pour into my family and friends more deeply, and to say yes to those I love more often. I’m looking forward to the big moments we’ll experience in 2023 🤰🏻🤱🏻 but mostly I’m looking forward to more of the sweet, simple, day to day joys that 2022 brought. 

I would love to know what made your 2022 special and/or what you’re looking forward to in 2023! 🤍

26 weeks with this little bebe and the weeks are just flying by! Anyone else feel like pregnancy went by faster and faster each time? 😮‍💨 Like it’s hard to sit back and just enjoy being pregnant when you feel like you’re drowning in your to-do list and taking care of your family? 

I don’t have near as many belly photos this time around, I haven’t done any sort of nesting, and at this rate baby isn’t even going to have a name by the time they arrive. 🙃 This little baby is SO incredibly loved but I’m just feeling kind of sad that I haven’t felt fully present this time around. Some days I practically forget I’m pregnant. I feel really good (which is a huge blessing I know) and I don’t feel this baby kick all that often (thanks anterior placenta 😑), so most days I just feel pretty normal. And not knowing the gender is so so exciting but also creates the slightest disconnect for me. I struggle to picture who this baby will be. Don’t get me wrong, I am SO excited for what I think will be the best surprise ever, but I also enjoyed feeling like I ‘knew’ who was in there with my boys. I felt like I could picture them in our family a bit more vividly. Anyhow, vowing to make the most of these last 14 or so weeks and if you’re in the same boat as me just know you’re not alone! 🤍

Third time around and the excitement and anxiety of preparing for a newborn feels almost as fresh as the first! 🕊️🤍 Drop your top newborn must haves (or wants) in the comments👇🏻 and save this post if there’s a baby in your future so you can come back to all these ideas! 

Here are some of my newborn must-haves followed by some nice-to-haves…
• kimono onesies (these are my fav for the first couple weeks for easy diaper changes) 
• muslin burp clothes (buy the big pack, you’ll be glad you did) 
• diapers diapers diapers (@believediapers are our favorite and having a diaper subscription will ensure you don’t run out)
• swaddles or a quilt for baby to lay over them when nursing or when you’re holding them 
• baby shampoo and diaper cream
• a nursing pillow (this one is a personal preference thing but for me a nursing pillow is a must, love my @boppycompany pillow)
• nasal aspirator (loved the @fridababy one with my second) 
• a changing pad for at home and on the go (@makemakeorganics makes a nice one that can be easily washed or @gathre micro mats can be easily wiped down)
• an electric nail file because baby nails are scary and trust me when I say the electric file makes trimming so much easier 
• a baby bath seat (I used the Anglecare seat with my boys but there are lots of options out there)
• a soft wrap for the moments you need your hands but want baby close (I love @sollybaby wraps)
• a lounger so you can safely set your baby down (I love both the @snuggle_me_organic and @charliecraneparis rocker)
• a car seat cover to keep baby safely covered when out (@theovercompany makes our favorite covers)
• a stroller with a bassinet attachment made walks so much easier with my second (we adore the @babyzenstrollers Yoyo stroller) 

Phew, I know there are more but those are just some that come to mind immediately! I’ll share my must-haves for mom in the coming weeks too, because honestly I feel like I always need more than my babies in those early days. 😮‍💨

There is something so special but so bittersweet about preparing for your last baby. ✨ Even the simple act of pulling old baby clothes out of storage has me feeling all emotional. I’m lingering a little longer on these moments knowing this’ll be the last time I experience the joy of this season. 

Everyone always talks about how exciting that first baby is (and it truly is 🥹). There is so much excitement and anticipation for all the firsts…

The first time you stare in awe (or shock or disbelief) at a positive pregnancy test. 

The first time you hear your baby’s heartbeat and see them wiggling on the ultrasound screen. 

Those first kicks. 

The first time you lay eyes on them and the first time they’re placed on your chest. 

The absolute joy of seeing that first smile, watching that first roll, and seeing them crawl, walk, and talk for the first time…

The firsts are so exciting and with your first baby they’re extra sweet. But no one really prepares you for how bittersweet that last baby is. How bittersweet it is knowing that this season of firsts is also a season lasts 😭…

The last time you’ll stare in awe (or shock or disbelief) at a positive pregnancy test. 

The last time you’ll hear your baby’s heart beating from inside. 

The last time you’ll feel those baby kicks. 

The last time you’ll experience labor and birth. 

The last time you’ll smell that newborn smell (on one of your own babies at least). 

The last time you’ll experience the joy of watching your baby smile for the first time, learn to crawl, or take their first steps. 

It’s a bit of a double edged sword when you know it’s your last. Ive been more mindful and conscious of soaking up all these little moments I’ll never experience again but the knowledge this is the last time stings a little. 🥺 I feel such peace knowing this is our last baby. When I picture our (soon to be) family of five, it feels so complete. But dang, that last baby just hits different.

I know I say this every week but I REALLY can’t believe we hit 28 weeks on Monday. We are in the third trimester now and I’m on bi-weekly midwife appointments. Starting to finalize birth plans and feeling the urge to get things a bit more ready for baby. Things are really getting real over here. 😳 And as excited as I am to meet this baby, I’m really wanting time to slow down. I love being pregnant and feel like it’s going to be over before I know it. We’ve also got a few major things to take care of, like oh figuring out a name and finding a new vehicle to fit our family of five, that I could use some extra time for. 🫠

I truly love being pregnant. I think I have fairly ‘easy’ pregnancies, in so much as pregnancy can be called easy. But this baby is taking me on a bit of a wild ride over here. 😮‍💨 If you saw my stories yesterday you’ll know I’ve had somewhat high blood pressure my last two appointments. While my midwife isn’t overly concerned yet, it’s something that needs to be monitored. I’m keeping a close eye on it with my little at blood pressure monitor. Obviously when the slightest thing goes wrong you spiral, go down the google rabbit hole, and imagine all the worst case scenarios. My fingers are crossed that with a couple of lifestyle changes and adding some additional supplements, I’ll get things more under control. 🤞🏻

And thank you to everyone who reached out with advice, shared experiences, or just offered words of encouragement. It’s so reassuring knowing you’re not alone in these situations! 🥰 Now if things could just chill for the next 12 weeks and I could deliver a healthy, full-term baby in the comfort of my home, that would be great. 🫠

My sweet baby boy. My soon-to-be middle child. I can’t believe he’ll be a big brother in just two month’s time. 🐻

I’m feeling more than a little emotional and more than a lot nervous for all the change that’s about to come his way. He totally understands there is a baby coming. He’s constantly touching my belly and saying “I love you baby.” But I’m just so nervous for how this transition is going to turn his world upside down. He is so sweet and sensitive. He’s a true mama’s boy and wants to be around me no matter what I’m doing. He loves cuddling while he falls asleep and still climbs into bed to snuggle every morning. And he wants me to do all the things for him… dress him, change him, wipe his nose, you name it, it’s gotta be mom. When baby comes my arms will be occupied most of the time, that extra space in our bed will be taken, and there will probably be a few more no’s or not right Joe’s in this little guy’s life and that makes me sad. I don’t doubt that we’ll figure it out but I’d be lying if I said my heart didn’t hurt to think about these changes.

There are so many benefits to baby wearing and I’m really embracing it with my third baby! 🤱🏻 Here are just 5 of my favorite benefits…

1. Helps baby feel safe and secure as they transition from the dark, warm familiarity of the womb to the outside world. Carried babies also cry less!

2. Keeps your hands free while keeping baby close! I’ve done dishes, folded laundry, read books, played with my older kiddos, made meals, and even used the bathroom 🫠 while baby wearing.

3. It’s healthy for baby. Did you know that baby wearing counts as tummy time!? It helps them build muscle, hold their head up, and can help prevent a flat head. 

4. It’s beneficial for mom. Skin to skin contact and holding your baby close not only helps you bond with your baby but also promotes the release of oxytocin. Oxytocin helps reduce stress and has even been shown to help with postpartum depression. 

5. Keeps unwanted hands away. This might be my favorite one! It’s a great way to avoid playing pass the baby and keeps unwanted hands off your little one while you’re out and about. I always feel more in control when I’m baby wearing.

I’m a planner girly through and through. If it’s not written down in my planner, it’s probably not happening. 🫠 Here are five tips for using a planner to keep your days organized…

1 Set aside designated time each week to plan. I like to do this on Sunday so we start our week off organized. Make a habit of this and you’ll come to look forward to your weekly planning time! ⏰ 

2 Use a planner to keep things in one place. Being able to open my planner and see my full week at a glance, plus all your deadlines, to-do list, meal plan, etc keeps me from feeling overwhelmed. I know if I need information about our week it’s in my planner. 😉 

3 color code by categories so you can see commitments at a glance. I have different colors for things like appointments, social activities, bills, and daily tasks. This allows me to open my planner and quickly find the information I need! 🎨 

4 allocate specific tasks to days of the week and keep it consistent. This makes weekly planning easier and I’ve found it helps our weeks flow smoothly. For example, Mondays are our grocery shopping day so I know in advance not to schedule other commitments that day. 📆

5 find a system that works for you and stay flexible. This is what works for me and while I hope some of these tips are helpful, the most important thing is finding what works for you! Annnnd even when you plan your week perfectly, things won’t always go according to plan, so don’t forget to stay flexible! 🤸

Save this recipe for an easy, delicious, and healthier swap for store bought fruit snacks! 💁🏻‍♀️ My kids and I are obsessed with these 3-ingredient homemade gummies! Here’s how to make them…

🤍 pour 4 cups of your favorite juice into a small pot
🤍 sprinkle 8tbsp of unflavored beef gelatin over top and let it bloom for a couple of minutes
🤍 turn the heat on, give it a stir (don’t overmix or it’ll get a white film on top) and bring to a slight simmer 
🤍 add honey to taste (I used about 1/4 cup)
🤍 heat until dissolved 
🤍 pour into a glass baking dish or gummy molds if you want 
🤍 put in fridge and let set for a couple of hours 
🤍 cut into small cubes and store in fridge (they’ll last 2 weeks or so, but they’ll be gone before then 😉)
